Here are five countries with the lowest population in West Africa based on area covered amongst neighbouring countries and United Nations Data: 1. Liberia Liberia is bordered by Sierra Leone to its northwest, Guinea to the north, Ivory Coast to its East and Atlantic Ocean to iits south and Southwest. Its total current population is 5,271,183 as of Thursday, April 21, 2022, based on Worldometer elaboration of the latest United Nations data and it covers an area of 111,369 square kilometers (43,000 sq mi). 		 			Top five Nollywood movies on Netflix in 2022		 		 		 			Queen Elizabeth gets Barbie doll to mark 70years on throne		 		 		 			Celebrities that have announced pregnancies in 2022		 		 2. Cape Verde Cape Verde or Cabo Verde is an archipelago and island country in the central Atlantic Ocean, consisting of ten volcanic islands with a combined land area of about 4,033 square kilometres (1,557 sq mi). Cabo Verde 2020 population is estimated at 555,987 people at mid-year according to UN data. 3. Guinea Bissau Republic of Guinea Bissau covers 36,125 square kilometres (13,948 sq mi) with a population of 1,726,000. It borders Senegal to the North and Guinea to the South-East. The current population of Guinea-Bissau is 2,051,540 as of Thursday, April 21, 2022, based on Worldometer elaboration of the latest United Nations data. 4. The Gambia Gambia is the smallest nation within mainland Africa. It is surrounded by Senegal, except for its western coast on the Atlantic Ocean. The current population of Gambia is 2,538,584 as of Thursday, April 21, 2022, based on Worldometer elaboration of the latest United Nations data. 5. Mauritania Islamic Republic of Mauritania is a Northwest African sovereign state bordered by the Atlantic Ocean to the west, Western Sahara to the north and northwest, Algeria to the northeast, Mali to the east and southeast, and Senegal to the southwest. It has an average population of 4,869,139.